avirus Fans Religious Hatred|first1=Jeffrey|last1=Gettleman|first2=Kai|last2=Schultz|first3=Suhasini|last3=Raj|date=April 12, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2020/04/14/coronavirus-muslims-islamophobia/|title=The Coronavirus Is Empowering Islamophobes \u2014 but Exposing the Idiocy of Islamophobia|first=Mehdi|last=Hasan|date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> Mob cases were reported by the [[news media]] after some people related to the missionary were tested positive for [[pandemic]] of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], though infectious disease spread [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|worldwide]] with thousands of deaths since it originated in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/03/28/india-delhi-first-came-the-pogroms-now-theres-coronavirus/|title=In Delhi, First Came the Pogroms. Then Came Coronavirus.|first=Yashraj|last=Sharma}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/coronavirus/covid-19-rumours-linked-to-3-attacks-in-delhi-gurgaon-6350696/|title=COVID-19 rumours linked to 3 attacks in Delhi, Gurgaon|date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The pandemic triggered severe [[Strike (attack)|attack]]s on the minorities, leading to violence between followers of different religions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/12/briefing/coronavirus-india-anti-muslim-attacks.html|title=Anti-Muslim Attacks, Boris Johnson, China's New Cases: Your Monday Briefing|first=Melina|last=Delkic|date=April 12, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/17/technology/17reuters-health-coronavirus-india-muslims-insight.html|title=In Modi's India, Virus Fallout Inflames Divisions Between Muslims and Hindus|newspaper=The New York Times|date=April 17, 2020}}</ref> An Indian novelist and activist [[Arundhati Roy]] claimed the [[sectarian violence]] \"approaching to genocide\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/indias-treatment-of-muslims-amid-coronavirus-is-almost-genocidal-activist-arundhati-roy-claims/a-53167812|title=India's treatment of Muslims amid coronavirus is almost 'genocidal,' activist Arundhati Roy claims &#124; DW &#124; 17.04.2020|first=Deutsche|last=Welle (www.dw.com)|website=DW.COM}}</ref><ref name=\"Desk 2020\">{{cite web | last=Desk | first=Web | title=India should protect rights of Muslims amid COVID-19 crisis: OIC - Pakistan | website=The News International | date=19 April 2020 | url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/646709-india-should-protect-muslim-minoritys-rights-amid-covid-19-crisis-islamophobia-oic | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> The #CoronaJihad [[hashtag]] has been distributed 300,000 times on [[social media]] during this period.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5815264/coronavirus-india-islamophobia-coronajihad/|title=It Was Already Dangerous To Be Muslim in India. Then Came the Coronavirus|website=Time}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSince the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] case was detected in India on 30 January 2020, the [[Religious violence in India|religious violence]] sparked among the people from different adherents, especially Hindus accusing [[Minority religion|minorities]] for infecting the citizens of the country, though the [[Government of India]] did not took measures to stop religious activities at the earliest.<ref name=\"RFI 2020\">{{cite web | title=Coronavirus pandemic used to stir-up anti-Muslim prejeudice in India | website=RFI | date=13 April 2020 | url=http://www.rfi.fr/en/international/20200413-coronavirus-pandemic-used-to-stir-up-anti-muslim-prejeudice-in-india | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"voa\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.voanews.com/extremism-watch/coronavirus-spread-india-sparks-intolerance-toward-minority-muslims|title=Coronavirus Spread in India Sparks Intolerance Toward Minority Muslims &#124; Voice of America - English|website=www.voanews.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.thewire.in/article/communalism/coronavirus-anti-muslim-propaganda-india|title=The Coronavirus Has Morphed Into an Anti-Muslim Virus|website=The Wire}}</ref> Tablighi Jamaat, a Muslim missionary held several [[Ijtema|congregation]]s in the country, claiming in rise of coronavirus cases before [[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|lockdown was imposed]] in the country.<ref name=\"Beydoun 2020\">{{cite web | last=Beydoun | first=Khaled A. | title=Between virus and violence: The horror of being Muslim in India | website=alaraby | date=17 April 2020 | url=https://english.alaraby.co.uk/english/comment/2020/4/17/between-virus-and-violence-being-muslim-in-india | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref> It is claimed that [[Hindus]] were also actively involved in organising religious debates,<ref name=\"voa\"/> including [[Uttar Pradesh]] chief minister [[Yogi Adityanath]] attended a congregation at a Hindu temple, comprised hundreds of attendees during the nationwide lockdown.<ref name=\"The New York Times1\"/><ref name=\"Jha 2020\">{{cite web | last=Jha | first=Nishita | title=The Coronavirus In India: 200 Million Muslims Blamed For Spread Of COVID-19 After 6 Deaths Tied To One Mosque | website=BuzzFeed News | date=3 April 2020 | url=https://www.buzzfeednews.com/article/nishitajha/coronavirus-india-muslims-tablighi-jamaat | access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Social media controversies==\nThe political leaders, including 25 members of [[Bharatiya Janata Party]] termed the islamic conference or congregation \"#coronaJihad\", \"#CoronaTerrorism\" and \"#CoronaBombsTablighi\" using the hashtags that were subsequently circulated by the [[internet users]] across the social media, including Twitter.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/13/coronavirus-conspiracy-theories-targeting-muslims-spread-in-india|title=Coronavirus conspiracy theories targeting Muslims spread in India|first=Hannah Ellis-Petersen Shaikh Azizur Rahman in|last=Kolkata|newspaper=The Guardian|date=April 13, 2020|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/> An Indian politician and former wrestler [[Babita Phogat]] wrote on Twitter stating that Jamaati are bigger problem than even the virus.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52320900|title=India stars under fire for 'anti-Muslim' tweets|work=BBC News|date=April 17, 2020|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> Her tweet was later criticised by the several people using \"#SupendBabitaPhogat\" [[Twitter]] hashtag.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/babita-phogat-faces-backlash-over-controversial-tweets-on-tablighi-jamaat-1668008-2020-04-17|title=Babita Phogat faces backlash over controversial tweets on Tablighi Jamaat|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiApril 17|first2=2020UPDATED|last2=April 17|first3=2020 15:18|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref> Some Indian employees working with Dubai-based private companies suffered [[termination of employment]] for allegedly sharing coronavirus violence-related posts on social media.<ref name=\"PTI 2020\">{{cite web | author=PTI | title=Another Indian expat in UAE sacked over Islamophobic post | website=The Hindu | date=13 April 2020 | url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/another-indian-expat-in-uae-sacked-for-islamophobic-post/article31328980.ece | access-date=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Role of administration==\nThe Indian police of the [[Maharashtra]] state charged over 200 people linked to the missionary congregation for allegedly spreading COVID-19 in the country, though health officials argue that government linked the Muslims to pandemic unfavorably.<ref name=\"Ulmer 2020\">{{cite web | last=Ulmer | first=Alexandra | title=In Modi's India, virus fallout inflames divisions between Muslims and Hindus | website=U.S. | date=17 April 2020 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-india-muslims-insi-idUSKBN21Z0LN | access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Middle East Monitor 2020\">{{cite web | title=Saudi scholar calls for expulsion of Hindu supremacists from the Gulf | website=Middle East Monitor | date=17 April 2020 | url=https://www.middleeastmonitor.com/20200417-saudi-scholar-calls-for-expulsion-of-hindu-supremacists-from-the-gulf/ | access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> In India, thirty-two people associated to the missionary are confirmed dead out of total 1,251, while Pakistan has reported twenty missionary-linked deaths out of 1,914.<ref name=\"Miglani 2020\">{{cite web | last=Miglani | first=Sanjeev | title=India and Pakistan crack down on Muslim group emerging as COVID-19 cluster | website=IN | date=31 March 2020 | url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-southasia-idINKBN21I0Z0 | access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> The [[Foreign Affairs]] magazine held the Indian as well as Pakistan government responsible for intense [[List of deaths due to coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19 fatalities]] due to lack of scientific medical establishments and unavailability of modern medicine. The [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) stated in its report that coronavirus is [[Transmission (medicine)|passing]] in India through [[Social|local gathering]]s not through arrival of people with the history of foreign travelling.<ref name=\"Krishnan 2020\">{{cite web | last=Krishnan | first=Vidya | title=Coronavirus Threatens Catastrophe in India | website=Foreign Affairs | date=3 April 2020 | url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/india/2020-03-25/coronavirus-threatens-catastrophe-india | access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:Hinduism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Islam-related controversies in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 crimes in India]]\n[[Category:Religiously motivated violence in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India]]\n[[Category:2020 in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}